body:
When an assertion depends on an external template type, Psalm flattens it too early, which makes it think the type is `T as mixed`.

Example 1 (https://psalm.dev/r/09cce75778):
```php
<?php
/**
 * @template T
 */
class Clazz
{
    /**
     * @param mixed $x
     *
     * @return bool
     *
     * @psalm-assert-if-true T $x
     */
    public function is($x) : bool {
        return true;
    }
}

/**
 * @template T
 *
 * @param Clazz<T> $c
 *
 * @return T|false
 */
function example(Clazz $c) {
    /** @var mixed */
    $x = 0;
    return $c->is($x) ? $x : false;
}

/** @var Clazz<int> */
$c = new Clazz();
example($c);
```

Example 1 output:
```
INFO: MixedAssignment - 28:5 - Cannot assign $x to a mixed type

ERROR: InvalidReturnStatement - 29:12 - The type 'false|Tasmixed' does not match the declared return type 'T as mixed|false' for example

ERROR: InvalidReturnType - 24:12 - The declared return type 'T|false' for example is incorrect, got 'false|Tasmixed'
```

Since return types are resolved later when the templated type is known, they don't cause the same issue.

Example 2 (https://psalm.dev/r/ce7c41e2c1):
```php
<?php
/**
 * @template T
 */
class Clazz
{
    /**
     * @param mixed $x
     *
     * @return T
     */
    public function is($x) {
        /** @var T */
        return true;
    }
}

/**
 * @template T
 *
 * @param Clazz<T> $c
 *
 * @return T
 */
function example(Clazz $c) {
    /** @var mixed */
    $x = 0;
    return $c->is($x);
}

/** @var Clazz<int> */
$c = new Clazz();
example($c);
```

Example 2 output:
```
Psalm output (using commit 3df248e):

INFO: MixedAssignment - 27:5 - Cannot assign $x to a mixed type
```

Could support be added for this usage?
